## Part 2 — Complete TikTok Automation Guide

### The fundamental difference between YouTube and TikTok automation

YouTube automation can tolerate slower pipelines, longer content, and more deliberate SEO work. TikTok automation is a different discipline entirely:

- Videos are 15–60 seconds (occasionally 3 minutes for TikTok Stories)
- The first 2 seconds determine whether anyone watches
- The algorithm is discovery-first, not search-first — hashtags and keywords matter less than watch-through rate and shares
- Posting frequency matters more: 1–3 videos per day consistently outperforms 7 videos once a week
- 9:16 vertical format is mandatory
- Native audio (trending sounds) performs better than external voiceover, but is unavailable via API — automation must compensate with strong scripting and visual pacing

---

## The full TikTok automation stack

### Layer 1 — Content research & trend detection

Unlike YouTube where keyword research dominates, TikTok success depends on spotting trends early. Your automation needs:

**Trend scraping (unofficial, fragile but powerful):**
- `tiktok-scraper` (npm) or `TikTokApi` (Python) to pull trending videos by hashtag or sound
- Parse the top 50 videos in your niche daily, extract hooks, formats, and topic clusters
- Feed those patterns to an LLM to generate variations, not copies

**Official research tools:**
- TikTok Creative Center (manual, but has a trends API for Business accounts)
- Google Trends + Reddit scraping for topic signals before they hit TikTok
- YouTube Shorts trending — TikTok trends often appear on Shorts 48–72 hours later

**Recommended pipeline:** Cron job at 6 AM daily → scrape top 50 trending videos in niche → extract hook patterns and topics → LLM generates 5 script candidates → human or automated selection → enter production queue.

---

### Layer 2 — Script writing for short-form

TikTok scripts follow a rigid structure that differs entirely from YouTube:

```
[0–2s]   HOOK — pattern interrupt, bold claim, or curiosity gap
[2–8s]   SETUP — one sentence of context
[8–45s]  VALUE — the actual content, delivered fast
[45–55s] CTA — "follow for more", "comment X if...", "share this"
```

When prompting an LLM for TikTok scripts:
- Specify word count: ~130 words for a 60-second video at natural speech pace
- Require the hook to be the first sentence, no preamble
- Avoid transitions like "Now," "So," "As we can see" — these kill watch time
- Request 3 hook variants per script so you can test which performs

Example system prompt addition:
```
Write a TikTok script for: {topic}
- First sentence must be the hook. No greeting, no intro.
- Total length: 120–140 words
- Tone: {niche_tone}
- End with one engagement CTA
- Provide 3 alternative opening hooks at the bottom
```

---

### Layer 3 — Video production (the core gap)

This is where most automation repos fail. For TikTok specifically, you have three viable approaches:

**Option A: Faceless stock footage + voiceover (easiest)**

The MoneyPrinterTurbo approach. Works well for educational, news, facts, and listicle content.

Stack:
- MoneyPrinterTurbo (harry0703/MoneyPrinterTurbo) — handles script → stock footage → TTS → subtitles → MP4
- Set `video_aspect` to `9:16` in config
- Use Chatterbox or Fish Audio for higher-quality TTS than the defaults
- Add word-by-word subtitle highlighting (use the Asad-Ismail/MoneyPrinterTurbo-Extended fork)

Weaknesses: stock footage looks generic and audiences are increasingly good at recognizing it.

**Option B: AI image storyboard (what sahil0202 does)**

Good for: story channels, history, mythology, motivational, horror narrative, "imagine if" formats.

Stack:
- sahil0202/Youtube_Automation with `USE_VEO=false` for fast generation
- Force 9:16: set `VEO_ASPECT_RATIO=9:16` and ensure image generation uses portrait dimensions
- Add pan-and-zoom (Ken Burns effect) to static images using FFmpeg:
  ```
  ffmpeg -loop 1 -i image.jpg -vf "zoompan=z='min(zoom+0.001,1.5)':d=125:x='iw/2-(iw/zoom/2)':y='ih/2-(ih/zoom/2)',scale=1080:1920" -t 5 out.mp4
  ```
- This makes static image content look significantly more professional

**Option C: AI video generation (highest quality, highest cost)**

For premium channels where quality justifies compute cost.

Stack:
- Wan 2.2 or HunyuanVideo for clip generation (self-hosted GPU)
- ComfyUI with TikTok-optimized workflows (9:16 native output)
- Generate 4–6 short clips (3–5s each) per video, stitch with FFmpeg
- Add Chatterbox TTS voiceover and burn-in subtitles

Compute requirement: RTX 4090 or cloud GPU (Lambda Labs ~$0.80/hr). A 60-second video needs ~6 clips at 12–18 min each on an RTX 3080 → ~2 hours render time. Plan your queue accordingly.

---

### Layer 4 — Post-production essentials

TikTok-specific post-production that automation must handle:

**Subtitles (mandatory):**
TikTok is often watched without sound. Auto-generate subtitles using Whisper (OpenAI, open source) and burn them into the video:
```python
import whisper
model = whisper.load_model("base")
result = model.transcribe("voiceover.mp3")
# Generate .srt from result["segments"]
# Burn with FFmpeg: -vf subtitles=output.srt
```
Style: large white text, black stroke, centered in lower third. Not small captions — TikTok-sized bold text.

**Safe zone padding:**
TikTok UI overlays the bottom 20% (username, caption, audio bar) and right side (action buttons). Keep all text and important visual content in the center 60% of the frame.

**Aspect ratio enforcement:**
Every video must be exactly 1080×1920 (9:16) or TikTok will add letterbox bars, which kills engagement. Add an FFmpeg normalize step:
```
ffmpeg -i input.mp4 -vf "scale=1080:1920:force_original_aspect_ratio=increase,crop=1080:1920" output.mp4
```

**Duration:**
15–34 seconds: best for discovery and loop plays
35–60 seconds: best for saves and shares (algorithm rewards this)
60–180 seconds: only works if you have an existing audience

